data.content:
Yes — use **strongly-typed tuples** to avoid the `object[]` boxing and get compile-time safety:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Why this is better:**
- **Type safety** — no casting from `object[]`; mismatched types are caught at compile time
- **Named fields** — tuple names document intent
- **Cleaner syntax** — parentheses instead of brackets

> **Note:** Typed tuple support in `[DynamicData]` requires **MSTest v3.8+**. If you're on an older version, you'd need to stick with `object[]` or use `[DataRow]` for simple inline cases:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

`[DataRow]` is the simplest option when your data is constant and the types are primitives.
